# AWS Infrastructure — {{companyName}}

## When to Use
- Designing cloud architecture or selecting AWS services
- Writing IaC (CloudFormation, CDK, Terraform for AWS)
- Debugging CloudWatch logs or AWS service issues
- IAM policy design and security hardening

## Architecture Principles
1. **Well-Architected Framework** — Follow the 6 pillars: Operational Excellence, Security, Reliability, Performance Efficiency, Cost Optimization, Sustainability
2. **Least Privilege** — IAM policies should grant minimum required permissions
3. **Defense in Depth** — Multiple security layers (VPC, SGs, NACLs, WAF)
4. **Immutable Infrastructure** — Prefer replacement over in-place updates

## Service Selection Guide

| Need | Recommended Service |
|------|-------------------|
| Compute | Lambda (serverless), ECS/Fargate (containers), EC2 (VMs) |
| Storage | S3 (objects), EFS (files), EBS (block) |
| Database | RDS/Aurora (relational), DynamoDB (NoSQL), ElastiCache (cache) |
| Messaging | SQS (queues), SNS (pub/sub), EventBridge (events) |
| Networking | VPC, ALB/NLB, CloudFront (CDN), Route 53 (DNS) |

## Security Checklist
- [ ] Enable CloudTrail for audit logging
- [ ] Use AWS Secrets Manager for credentials
- [ ] Enable VPC Flow Logs
- [ ] Configure S3 bucket policies (no public access by default)
- [ ] Enable encryption at rest (KMS)
- [ ] Use Security Hub for posture management

## Cost Optimization
- Use Savings Plans or Reserved Instances for predictable workloads
- Enable Cost Explorer and set billing alerts
- Right-size instances using Compute Optimizer recommendations
- Use S3 Intelligent-Tiering for variable access patterns
